== Overview ==

[[File:Kasuga mukaiyama kohun aerial.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Aerial view of Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun<br>(1985)}}{{small|{{National Land Aerial Photography}}.}}]]
The '''Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun''' (春日向山古墳) is a large square tumulus located in the {{ill|Isonokami Tumulus Cluster|ja|磯長谷古墳群}} at the southwestern edge of the Kasuga settlement, near the foot of {{ill|Mount Nijo (Osaka)|ja|二上山}}, in {{ill|Taishi, Osaka|ja|太子町}}. Managed by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁}} as a designated mausoleum for {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|ja|用明天皇}}, it has not been fully excavated. However, a research organization was allowed to conduct an on-site inspection in {{ill|2012|ja|平成24年}}.<ref>[https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXNASDG2300T_T20C12A2CC0000/ "Researchers Gain Access to Yōmei Mausoleum in Osaka"] (Nikkei Shimbun, February 23, 2012).</ref>

The mound is square, facing south, and presumed to have three construction tiers. The mound measures 65m east-to-west, 60m north-to-south, and 10m in height. Surrounding the mound is a moat approximately 7m wide.<ref name="Taishi">[http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/kanko_info/rekishi_shiseki/yomeitennoryo.html Yōmei Mausoleum] (Taishi Town Homepage).</ref> Including the moat's outer embankment, the tumulus spans 100m east-to-west and 90m north-to-south.<ref name="Taishi"/> No {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪}} have been found on the surface.<ref name="Taishi"/>

The burial chamber is not exposed, but documents from 1725 (Kasuga Village Yoshimura Family Archives) suggest the presence of a horizontal stone chamber.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=|author=|year=1986|chapter=Mukaiyama Kofun|title=Japanese Historical Place Names Encyclopedia 28 Osaka Prefecture|publisher=Heibonsha|isbn=458249028X}}</ref> Additionally, the {{ill|Byōryōki|ja|廟陵記}} mentions exposed large stones that may be related to the chamber.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=|author=Tetsuya Takashima|year=1989|chapter=Yōmei Mausoleum Kofun|title=Japanese Kofun Encyclopedia|publisher=Tokyo-do Shuppan|isbn=4490102607}}</ref>

The tumulus is believed to date to the early {{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀}} and shows design similarities to the {{ill|Ishibutai Kofun|ja|石舞台古墳}} (associated with {{ill|Soga no Umako|ja|蘇我馬子}}).<ref name="Taishi"/> Currently, the Imperial Household Agency designates it as the mausoleum of {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|ja|用明天皇}}, who passed away in {{ill|587|ja|587年}}.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=|author=|year=1994|chapter=Yōmei Mausoleum|title=The Valley of Royal Tombs and the Isonokami Tumulus Cluster|publisher=Taishi Town Education Board|pages=15-16}}</ref>

== Possible Interred Individual ==

Although the actual occupant is unknown, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁}} designates the tumulus as the mausoleum of {{ill|Emperor Yōmei|ja|用明天皇}}.<ref>[https://www.kunaicho.go.jp/ryobo/successive_list.html Imperial Mausoleums] (Imperial Household Agency).</ref><ref>{{NDLDC|1237123/12|陵墓要覧}} (1934, National Diet Library Digital Collection) 11 frames.</ref> According to the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀}}, Emperor Yōmei died in the second year of his reign (587) and was first buried at "Iware-no-ike-no-ue Mausoleum," then reinterred at "Kawachi Isonokahara Mausoleum" in {{ill|593|ja|593年}}.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Annotated Nihon Shoki (2)|publisher=Shogakukan|year=2004|p=532}}</ref>

If this tumulus is indeed his burial site, it would represent the first square tumulus designated as an Imperial mausoleum.<ref>{{Cite book|editor=|author=|year=1994|chapter=Yōmei Mausoleum|title=The Valley of Royal Tombs and the Isonokami Tumulus Cluster|publisher=Taishi Town Education Board|pages=15-16}}</ref>

