'''Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun''' (春日向山古墳) is an ancient Kofun located in {{ill|Taishi, Osaka|ja|太子町 (大阪府)|12=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft}}. The mound is part of the {{ill|Shinagadani Kofun Group|ja|磯長谷古墳群|1=Shinagadani Kofun Cluster|12=draft}} and has a square (''hōfun'') type.

Although the actual identity of the buried individual is unknown, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} has Historic Site1 this mound as the mausoleum of Emperor Yōmei, the 31st Emperor of Japan, under the name "'''Kawachi Shinagano Hara no Misasagi'''."

== Overview ==
[[File:Kasuga mukaiyama kohun aerial.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Aerial photograph of Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun<br>(1985)}}{{small|{{National Land Image Intypeation (Color Aerial Photographs)}}.}}]]

The Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun is a large square-shaped Kofun constructed on a terrace at the southwestern edge of the Kasuga settlement in the Shinagadani area, situated at the base of {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|1=Futakami Mountain|2=ja|3=二上山|lt=Mount Futakami (or Nijo)|comment=Kanji are ambiguous between the two pronounciations|12=draft}} in southeastern Osaka Prefecture. Currently managed as an imperial mausoleum by the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}}, no full-map_size excavations have been conducted. However, an academic survey was carried out in February 2012.<ref>[https://www.nikkei.com/article/DGXNASDG2300T_T20C12A2CC0000/ "Research Survey Conducted at Yōmei Mausoleum in Osaka"] (''Nikkei'', February 23, 2012).</ref>

The mound is square in type and faces south. The structure is estimated to have three tiers, measuring 65 meters east–west, 60 meters north–south, and 10 meters in height.<ref name="TaishiTown">[http://www.town.taishi.osaka.jp/kanko_info/rekishi_shiseki/yomeitennoryo.html Emperor Yōmei Mausoleum] (Taishi Town Website).</ref> Surrounding the mound is a moat approximately 7 meters wide, and the entire structure, including the outer embankments, reaches a total size of 100 meters east–west and 90 meters north–south. No {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft}} have been identified on the mound.<ref name="TaishiTown"/>

The burial facility has not been confirmed. However, historical records from the Edo period, including documents from the Yoshimura family of Kasuga, suggest the possibility of a {{ill|horizontal stone chamber|lt=yokona-style stone chamber|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft}}. The ''Byōryōki'' also mentions exposed large stones, potentially remnants of the chamber.<ref name="TaishiTown"/>

The Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun is estimated to have been constructed in the early {{ill|7th century|ja|7世紀|12=draft}}, during the late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft}}. Its design is noted to share similarities with the {{ill|Ishibutai Kofun|ja|石舞台古墳|12=draft}} in {{ill|Asuka, Nara|ja|明日香村|12=draft}}, suggesting a possible connection or shared architectural plan.<ref name="TaishiTown"/>

== Interred_individual ==
The actual individual buried within the Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun is unknown. However, the {{ill|Imperial Household Agency|ja|宮内庁|12=draft}} designates it as the mausoleum of Emperor Yōmei, who is said to have passed away in 587 and was originally buried at the {{ill|Iware Ikeue Mausoleum|ja|磐余池上陵|12=draft}} before being reinterred at this site.<ref>[https://www.kunaicho.go.jp/ryobo/successive_list.html Mausoleums] (Imperial Household Agency).</ref>

The mound represents one of the earliest square-shaped imperial tombs, marking a significant transition in the design of imperial burials during this period.<ref name="TaishiTown"/>

== Related Sites ==
The Kasuga Mukaiyama Kofun is part of the "Umebachi Mausoleums," a group of five imperial tombs in the Shinagadani Kofun Group, which also includes the tombs of Emperors Bidatsu, Suiko, and Kōtoku, as well as the burial site of Prince Shōtoku.<ref name="TaishiTown"/>

